05001nam a22006975i 9780748643233DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222010stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97807486432337 a10.1515/97807486432332doi  a(DE-B1597)614661  a(OCoLC)1302162746  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 4aPN1993.5.I8bB37 2010eb 7aPER0040002bisacsh04a791.4309542221 aBasu, Anustup, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBollywood in the Age of New Media :bThe Geo-televisual Aesthetic /cAnustup Basu. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b20 B/W illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tPart I: Introduction -- t1. Cinematic “Assemblages”: The 1990s and Earlier -- t2. The Geo- televisual and Hindi Film in the Age of Information -- tPart II: Informatics, Sovereignty, and the Cinematic City -- t3. Allegories of Power/Information -- t4. The Music of Intolerable Love: Indian Film Music, Globalization, and the Sound of Partitioned Selves -- tPart III: Myth and Repetition -- t5. Technopolis and the Ramayana: New Temporalities -- t6. Repetitions with Difference: Mother India and her Thousand Sons -- tEpilogue -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis study of popular Indian cinema in an age of globalisation, new media, and metropolitan Hindu fundamentalism focuses on the period from 1991 to 2004. Popular Hindi cinema took a certain spectacular turn from the early nineties as a signature 'Bollywood style' evolved in the wake of liberalization and the inauguration of a global media ecology in India. Films increasingly featured transformed bodies, fashions, life-styles, commodities, gadgets, and spaces, often in non-linear, 'window-shopping' ways, without any primary obligation to the narrative. Flows of desires, affects, and aspirations frequently crossed the bounds of stories and determined milieus. One example is the film Haqeeqat that featured poor working class protagonists, but romantic musical sequences transported them abruptly to Switzerland, with the actors now dressed in designer suits. Basu theorises this overall cinematic-cultural ecology here as an informational geo-televisual aesthetic. This book connects this filmic geo-televisual style to an ongoing story of the uneven globalizing process in India. Basu argues that 'Bollywood' is not so much indicative of a uniquely Indian modernity coming into its own; rather it is symptomatic of a pure techno-financial modernization that comes without a political modernity. Bollywood in the Age of New Media therefore explains how the irreverent energies of the new can actually be tied to conservative Brahminical imaginations of class, caste, or gender hierarchies. Using a wide-ranging methodological approach that converses with theoretical domains of post-structuralism, post-colonialism, and film and media studies, this book presents a complex account of an India of the present caught between brave new silicon valleys and farmer suicides.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aMotion picture industryzIndiazBombayxHistory. 0aMotion picture industryzIndiazMumbaixHistory. 0aMotion pictureszIndiaxHistory. 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074864102440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978074864323340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748643233423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748643233/or